Registered\" visual indicator for new ticket creation.\n\n\n**Implementing Micro-Interactions**\n\nI'm now implementing hover micro-interactions to create a highly responsive experience, focusing on micro-shifts, border lighting, and a spotlight card hover effect using `WorkspaceCard`. I am exploring clean transition and transform states for enhanced visual appeal and usability.\n\nI am also prioritizing an excellent responsive design. On mobile, the multi-column layout stacks elegantly. The interactive filter bar will collapse into a single drawer or simple flex row, while the ticket list and detail panels will stack smoothly with a back button. I've confirmed that the main implementation will be `/app/portal/support/page.tsx` while `/app/portal/support/[id]/page.tsx` must be tested.\n\n\n**Harmonizing the Routes**\n\nI'm now clarifying the relationship between the two routes. I realize that `/portal/support/[id]/page.tsx` should be a standalone premium ticket view, providing direct access, reply functionality, and a 'Back to Comm' link, maintaining consistency with `/portal/support/page.tsx`. This avoids redundant details pages, ensuring a seamless user experience. I'm also preparing ticket categories and a default mock ticket for local component state.\n\n\n**Persisting the State**\n\nI'm now integrating `localStorage` and `sessionStorage` for ticket persistence, aiming for a robust and senior-level implementation using React hooks or a lightweight utility. I'm focusing on seamless data loading and saving between the list and detail views, ensuring tickets persist across navigation. I'm also preparing to augment the mock ticket data from `lib/mock-data-model.ts` with categories and project IDs.\n\n\n**Expanding the Mock Data**\n\nI'm now populating the mock ticket data with realistic examples across all categories: Project Delivery, Billing, Documents, Access, Governance, and General. This enhanced data, including titles, categories, and project IDs, vastly improves the UI's completeness, allowing strategic presentation. I'm focusing on high-fidelity, expensive-feeling ticket representations.\n\nI'm also determining the filtering variables, including status (All Statuses, Open, In Progress, Resolved) and category (All Categories, Project Delivery, AI Operations).\n\n\n**Defining the Filters**\n\nI'm now expanding the filtering capabilities. I'm focusing on priority and project filters to create a modern layout. I'll include priority options like \"Critical\", \"High\", \"Medium\", and \"Low\" alongside project filters leveraging the `previewProjects` from the mock data. I'm excited about `lucide-react` icons such as `Filter`, `Search`, `MessageSquare` and others to support a user-friendly and aesthetically pleasing interface. The state structure for tickets will be initialized.\n\n\n**Initializing the Data**\n\nI'm now focusing on ensuring data persistence using `localStorage`. I'll load or generate augmented support tickets upon initialization, creating a rich mock dataset with realistic details. I'm prioritizing direct integration of the data loader within both `/portal/support/page.tsx` and `/portal/support/[id]/page.tsx`, confirming `localStorage` availability within Next.js, and working to implement an appropriate hook to manage it and persist.\n\n\n**Implementing Data Persistence**\n\nI'm now implementing the React state hooks and `localStorage` integration for data persistence to prevent hydration errors and ensure data loading. I've confirmed safe usage of `localStorage` by checking for `window` availability. I'll load existing tickets from local storage, generating initial tickets if none exist. I've planned an augmented ticket data list for robust loading, ensuring immediate data population and seamless data interaction.\n\n\n**Validating Enclave Communication**\n\nI'm now integrating new tickets with a focus on comprehensive handling of replies and their presentation, focusing on filtering, status updates, and user interactions. I'm focusing on the integration of data from real-time events, simulating telemetry logs within the UI, including a system notification, such as the event from Mercer, Vance, or the data from the described thread. I am focused on the seamless integration of responses for a highly interactive and informative user experience.\n\n\n**Integrating Real-time Events**\n\nI'm now focused on integrating real-time events, specifically handling replies and their UI presentation, alongside filtering, and status updates. I'm focusing on the integration of data from events, simulating telemetry logs within the UI, including system notifications for user feedback. This includes seamless integration of responses for a highly interactive and informative user experience. I am focusing on seamless integration of responses for a highly interactive and informative user experience, including a system notification, such as the event from Mercer, Vance, or the data from the described thread.\n\n\n**Simulating Telemetry Logs**\n\nI'm now diving deep into simulating telemetry logs within the UI and implementing system notifications for real-time user feedback. I'm focused on presenting event data from real-time sources such as Mercer, Vance, or the active thread. The goal is seamless replies and data integration to deliver a highly interactive and informative user experience. I've now integrated a new ticket and its replies.\n\n\n**Presenting Ticket Replies**\n\nI'm now integrating replies into existing tickets, focusing on `SLA-TKT-6541` and `SLA-TKT-5211`. I'm simulating telemetry events with system notifications to show an example data flow, including the SHA-256 seal from Mercer and Dr. Vance's response confirming the Ethereum/Sovereign-L2 ledger update. I am also working on rendering these replies in the enclave.\n\n\n**Refining the Replies**\n\nI'm now focusing on refining the display of ticket replies, particularly for `SLA-TKT-4122`. I'm integrating replies with associated senders and timestamps. I'm excited about including 'Security Bot' responses and the specified thread allocation, memory bounds, and timestamp information, presenting it elegantly within the enclave UI.\n\n\n**Defining the Filters**\n\nI'm now defining the filtering logic, creating state variables to manage search queries, statuses, categories, priorities, and projects. I'm building out a `filteredTickets` array, applying filters based on user selections and search criteria, ensuring comprehensive and responsive ticket filtering within the enclave.\n\n\n**Constructing the Form**\n\nI'm now building the ticket creation form with premium input selectors for Subject, Category, Priority, Linked Project, and Description, simulating telemetry diagnostics. On submission, I'll generate a unique ticket ID, set its status to \"open,\" record the creation date, and add it to the state. The form will then select the new ticket and display a premium \"Enclave Registered Successfully\" visual notification.\n\n\n**Designing the Detail Panel**\n\nNow I'm designing the detail panel, the \"Secure Communication Tunnel,\" for individual tickets. I'm focusing on its components: a header with essential ticket information, a telemetry log feed styled as a secure terminal, SLA countdown parameters, and the chat threads. I'm working on rendering replies in distinct, stylish boxes and implementing a form for client replies that trigger a simulated response.\n\n\n"}}
